commentText: Complimentary tech does end up eliminating farm workers. If you have 20 farmhands, but you can make 4 of them 400% more effective, you now have 4 people doing the work that it used to take all 20 to do. videoTitle: What Happens When Capitalism Doesn't Need Workers Anymore?
videoDescription: To get free fractional shares worth up to 100 EUR, you can open an account with Trading 212 through this link ...
commentText: A few thoughts.  For reference,  I teach industrial automation technologies how to set up, program, maintain and troubleshoot mechanical automation systems.  Setting up robotic assembly lines, building machines that build machines, etc.   I began teaching only a few years ago after many years in industry.   1. I was in the middle of the hollowing out of American manufacturing. Sometimes didn't know if I'd have a job next month because the plant was moving to overseas.  Also had to deal with many problems with parts and quality after those moves - and having to deal with supply chain when companies would decide to move their lines, but not build a product that directly replaced the one they quit making.  The corporate bottom line looked good, but the headaches from the people left was horrible, and worse, the devastation of the middle class was and is a reality.   2. The middle class is what made the US economy so strong, and it's a hollowed out shell.   Used to be, pretty much any job that wasn't flipping burgers was paying much more than minimum wage, and we didn't expect people to  go their entire lives on that pay.  It was for the kids in high school working part time or someone just out of school who was getting the entry level job that, in a month, or 3 or 6 was making much more than that.  Seriously, 20 years ago, minimum wage full time was less than 1% of the working population.   Actual middle class jobs were 75% of jobs (or more) and paid 10x that amount - AND you could afford to buy a car every couple of years, buy a house, and not have to go into future wage debt with credit cards.   Nowadays, people are trying to keep up appearances, but the US middle class is BROKE.    3. Companies have largely forgotten how to be loyal to employees. Used to be, you could get a job at age 20 or 25 and realistically could work there until retirement. And GROW, not just do the same job for 40 years.  The coming of the "gig economy" and the teaching by business schools of "interchangeable economic units" from a  Human Resources department had done a lot of the damage here.  Used to be, most middle and large sized companies had a significant training program in place where they would teach employees not only how to do their job, but also give them paths of advancement.   The disconnect between Wall Street and Main Street has choked that out.  For a long time,  you get hired for a job, and if you want a raise or a position advancement, you move somewhere else, instead of growing inside the company.    That seems to be changing a little... but not much. 4. These large tech corporations have done a marvelous job of publicly spreading risk while privately holding wealth - LLMs especially have been ripping off a lot of people from copyright, that, if it had been the other way, would have had the people getting sued - but the government has let the software companies get away with this "for the greater good" - even though it's pretty clear that LLMs are going to hurt a lot of people by not giving them a way into being productive. 5. Another dangerous thing about LLM - if it takes away the entry level "easy" tasks that are the training/honing tools for people to get good at, say, spotting cancers or other medical things - what happens in 10 or 20 years when all the current experts all die off? Who fills their shoes? If no one is allowed to get better because the job doesn't exist any more - then when there comes a time for the people to be there - where are they coming from?     Honestly, my field is the one area in manufacturing that still his hiring a lot of people - and we've kind of gone through that #5 part already - for many years the maintenance people didn't hire anyone because "well, we've got Bob, and Bob knows everything" - until Bob retires, or worse, drops dead from a heart attack...  now no one knows how to maintain the machines.  Smart companies have started waking up to that, and I keep praying the rest of industry does as well - but we've let too much money wreck the safeguards of government - and too many are focused on next quarter instead of next year or 5 years...   Meanwhile, I'm going to train as many people as I can, because when the robots do rise up, the people best able to defeat them are the ones who know how they work.

commentText: Recent studies have shown that "AI" hadn't produced any major improvements for 95% of respondent businesses. This makes sense when you consider that LLMs are good at exactly one thing: mimicking human language. They aren't good at reasoning, problem solving, or any of the actual cognitive labor they'd have to perform to actually replace human workers competently. This is a bubble that's just waiting to pop, propped up by greedy investors unwilling to let go of their unjustifiable sunk costs.

commentText: I worked at the intersection of strategic workforce planning, workforce development, and technology for over ten years. The assumption that we can just retrain everybody runs into serious problems every time I've seen it tested. (1) Many people in their 40's and 50's like what they were trained to do and are reasonably good at it. It isn't easy to tell someone who loves, let's say, working with animals, and tell them "Sorry, now you have to become an architect." (2) Many people, after 10-20 years of work experience, become pretty good at doing the EXACT JOB THEY ALREADY HAVE but would be pretty useless if asked to do anything else, even jobs that, on paper, look like the same job. (3) For the most part, people already have the most mentally / intellectually demanding job they can perform. Do not assume you can take a reasonably smart supply chain analyst who hasn't been to school in 15+ years and tell them "We'll train you to teach English in Japan, since AI can't do that yet." (4) Pretty soon, AI will be teaching English in Japan, so then what do you tell your ex-supply chain analyst ex-foreign English teacher to do then? Even if reskilling worked perfectly, it would take 3-5 years per reskilling.

commentText: As a millennial, with 8 years of professional experience in tech with 17 years of hobbyist experience, it is shit for us as well. I applied to 1,457 jobs before I landed a job with a local startup in a non-booming city. When i say startup, I mean me and the owner. That's it. I had to take this massive risk just to ensure I could pay rent after unemployment ran out here in the US. The best advice I can give is to do 2 things. Keep going, and get out into nature when you are not applying for jobs. Take a bus to go somewhere to hike. Get away from people as much as you can and refresh yourself.   Then try and find local job postings for SMALL businesses. And I mean small. Big tech will replace lower end employees faster than small mom and pop places who care about people. Aim to have enough, not excess. Learn to be content, not grinding. You will find happiness moment to moment, not in large clumps. And remember, when you eventually get something, be damn proud of yourself because it is fucking rough out there. Work hard, get into nature, and be at peace my friends. Hoping you all the best.

commentText: As a German product architect and senior software engineer, I am almost too annoyed to even say this anymore - but I will do so once more, so that some people may learn the truth:  it is NOT AI which is taking so many jobs. Our biggest clients all work in manufacturing, as we write SAP software, which is used throughtout most of the German manufacturing and automotive industry (and many more). As I am in charge of our AI development projects myself, and have even implemented the proof of concept AI basis using keras on tensorflow for our data mining AIs while using a locally hosted LLM for our LLM-based project proof, I know AI and I know the technology.  However, in none of these corporations you could claim that AI is being used in a production-ready context. We (as a thirdparty SAP-based software supplier) are way ahead of other competitors in the same field, as we have a few AI products already ready for use. However, those products are the only ones our customers have ever seen in their automation and system context. And to this day I have to essentially always start from 0, when talking to any customer about AI.  No, the industry IS NOT USING AI IN PRODUCTION. Corporations are using "AI" as a neat excuse for not hiring because their business is just so bad these days (which they tell us often, when we suggest large-scale projects as we did before Covid). First all corporations blamed covid for their bad numbers, then it was the Ukraine war and now it is AI. The reason changes but the effect is the same: A bad economic recession and the current scapegoat is "AI automation".  So please, when you hear a corporation is not hiring because they automated the position using AI, just know that they are not hiring because they simply cannot afford to pay you, as their business is going slowly right now. To this day I have not seen even one AI product in production - and our smallest customer has around 10k employees worldwide. So if even they are not using AI in production - who is!?  ---------------------------------  One more comment: And don't forget the irony, that so many people claim AI will be taking developer jobs. If I knew how, I would automate half my work in home-office and simply be payed the same for less effort. But no, AI is so damn stupid that it is like a self-writing wikipedia, but barely anything more. Just today I was using AI for reading up on a specific python framework's documentation, and the AI gave me a stupid suggestion on which API to use for a specific use case. The example the AI (claude 4) gave me already contained another API method which could be used instead, and made everything else unnecessary. But - being a stupid AI - I had to tell the AI exactly that, after which it obviously responded with "blablabla you are totally correct blablabla". So even though as a product architect on this subject, I am also the leading dev. on everything AI, I still did not find any way to get the AI to write useful code for us. Because I essentially have to tell the AI everything I told students, when I was teaching at a German university over 10 years ago. It's frustrating and makes no sense to even try - just hire someone who knows these things, instead of trying to "educate" an AI every time you see it doing some nonsense BS. Because no static prompt you can give the bot, will actually make it stick to your rules, as it arbitrarily ignores them.   So no - AIs are not going to take any complex or engineering jobs. But it will take jobs/tasks related to art or entertainment. Because in these jobs failure is not hard, but "only" results in a less satisfying customer experience, instead of a total production or process failure.

commentText: My go to: ask where they want you to be 1 week, 1 month, and before the end of the probationary period in terms of skill and independence. It 1. shows long term commitment and 2. makes them SEE YOU in that role. You've told them about your work history and made some basic rapport, now make them picture you in the role.   (I'm autistic and worked in HR. Most interviewers are zoned out at best, say something interesting or weirdly specific to make you stand out. I bring up projects that weren't company focused, but internally focused, making me seem more stable and long term. üëçüèΩ but also it is a tough job market even for the most qualified people... commentText: Italian here, you did an excellent job  explaining almost everything, but I would like to add another two things. Firstly, in many cases (but not always and there are many nuances) there is a toxic work culture whereby young people are "forced" to accept unfair conditions because otherwise the employers may argue that "young people just think about partying and aren't willing to make any sacrifices" (this is quite a common narrative here). Secondly, because Italy's population is quite old (and other factors), young people often find a stagnant environment, both economically and socially, shall I say, which can be suffocating. There are many things which could be said, but please look at the graph in 3:12. The regions of Emilia-Romagna and Lombardy receive many internal immgitants, because of the prestige of the oldest university in Europe and the financial capital of Italy respectively, which contribute to a more dynamic environment. On the other hand, (mainly) southern regions, which already have many issues to begin with and therefore a monotonous environment, see a large proportion of their young people leaving for other regions or other countries

commentText: I think you overlooked two major issues: 1. Recent graduates are often mistreated in our toxic work environments. They‚Äôre forced to either conform, push back and risk becoming toxic themselves, or leave the country. 2. There may be no pension system left for younger generations. The state pension plan, INPS, is often called a Ponzi scheme. Each generation funds the pensions of the current retirees, but workers are now outnumbered by pensioners. This makes the system unsustainable and likely to collapse within a couple of decades, leaving today‚Äôs young workers without a pension. People who are educated, speak a second language, and have in-demand skills are wisely seizing opportunities to leave as soon as they can.

commentText: I'm Italian, 24 years old, and lucky enough to work in the aviation industry, a field I‚Äôm passionate about, and one that pays relatively well. But even here, in what should be one of the most structured and respected sectors, the system is broken.  I graduated high school with 100/100, but still struggled to find meaningful work. My first job? Stocking shelves in an Amazon warehouse, because I had no experience, and few companies are willing to take a chance on someone fresh out of school. Eventually I made it into my field. And yes, I agree that aviation must have strict exams and standards, people‚Äôs lives are at stake. But even within major national institutions like ENAV, which manages all of Italy‚Äôs airspace, there are practices that, in my honest opinion, are just scummy.  Legally, you can only be employed on fixed-term contracts for 24 months total for the same role and employer. After that, the company must either justify the extension with a valid cause or convert it to a permanent (indefinite) contract. You‚Äôre only allowed four renewals, and there must be mandatory breaks between rehirings (10‚Äì20 days depending on contract length).  So what do companies do?  -they hire people for short stints (3 to 6 months) to avoid going over those thresholds; -they avoid calling it a renewal, even when you‚Äôre doing the exact same job, to bypass the limit on renewals; -they warn you upfront: "You can work here for a maximum of 2 or 3 years, then you're out."; -they require you to resubmit documents like ID, bank info, and criminal records each time, treating you like a new hire, even when you're returning after just a few weeks.  Yes, some of this is tied to compliance with security regulations or bureaucratic HR policies. But let‚Äôs be real: a lot of it is by design. The system is built to stay legal, tick the boxes for safety or anti-fraud, but still make it as easy as possible to avoid giving workers indefinite contracts (with all the protections, severance, and obligations that come with them).  How can a young person look at this and not want something better? How can someone not want a more stable, reliable and secure future for himself, and potential partner + family? Even "nerds" like me who poured over books, and were top of the class, are not safe from loopholes. All my life I've been told "just work hard and things will come"... My hard work got me in the field I studied for, but these fields were supposed to be different from the vast majority which take advantage of workers.  It was a rough wakeup call to realize even the dream places you wish to work at, follow the same tricks.  As long as the laws benefit the companies, and not the worker, the workers will of course go somewhere more stable.

commentText: The problem of low salaries in Italy is not related to the gross salary, which is not low, but rather to taxation. In Italy, the average cost per employee is ‚Ç¨55,000, while the amount actually earned, net of taxes, is ‚Ç¨25,000 ‚Äî less than half. In addition, VAT and fuel taxes are extremely high, in order to sustain a huge and complicated bureaucratic system. The purpose of this bureaucracy is to provide jobs to all those people working in the public sector, who would otherwise be unemployed.  If we then consider the large cities, rents are really high due to the high level of tourism. This means that those who do not own their home often struggle to cover costs, even while working hard, especially if they live alone.

commentText: Italy is a bureaucratic hell. You can't even get an ID without police showing up first at your home, every time you change cities you need a new ID. There is no national standardization on public services. You can't resolve or require anything online, every time you need some governmental document you need to waste your time going to a different public office that will probably be closed when it should be open. Taxes are crushing.  --  To those saying I am lying:  If you live in Italy you need to register your residency to the anagrafic office at the comune, up to date ID, Codice Fiscale, Tessera Sanitaria and SPID. Also there is all the problens involving paying the taxes regarding the trash, gas bill. In most of Italy you can do none of these online apart from SPID. To rent an apartment most landlords require references. And to get a bank account or a job you need a fixed address which you will be unable to have unless you already have a job. This kind of dynamic creates vicious cycles. If you have no close relatives or is not the kind of person who seeks friendships you are fucked.  You can't even have a prepaid cellphone line without presenting an ID. üòÇ  If you live in the capitals you can find some things online, otherwise you are screwed. commentText: I'm a Dane, and here's why I'm a happy tax payer.  At 17, I started suffering from debilitating chronic stomach pain, which lasted until I was 23, when I was finally diagnosed and got the right medication. In a matter of 2-3 years, I was symptom free, and in a few more years, I felt that the mental issues developed from living with a chronic disease had finally settled. At 31, I am living a completely normal life. I have critiques of the Danish healthcare system for some mismanagement of my disease (why did I have to suffer for 6 years?) but this isn't about my critiques, but my praise:  Due to my illness, it took me 8,5 years to finish a master's that should've taken 5,5 (managed to do the Master's on the numerated 2 after going through treatment and was so proud of that). Had I lived in the states, I would've been royally fucked. I would've had to drop my education or become severely indebted. As I had to study on less than full time, for obvious reasons, I couldn't have a job on the side - I could barely manage my studies. I was dependent on the student subsidies given to every student, as well as the low-rate loan available to students. I never had to stress about that part of the issue. I could stress about whether I'd ever be well again, whether I'd be able to hold down a job, etc. etc., but I NEVER DOUBTED I WOULD LIVE. Even if I'd have had to embrace a life of being severely disabled and living off the smallest subsidies, I would still have survived, I would still get medical aid, because in Denmark, we take care of each other.  Now, I'm on the other side and have worked full-time for 2 years at a well-paid job. I pay my high taxes happily, because I was given this opportunity, I was given that help, and that faith. I want to pass that on to others, and I want Denmark to remain a state where we are equal, where we all have basic human rights, where nobody is left in the gutter. When I calculate how much I've paid in taxes so far, I don't feel sad at lost money, I feel pride at my contribution.

commentText: I am danish, and while we love to complain about taxes, one cannot deny how much value we get for it. Schools are great, hospitals are modern and wait lists are usually not long, our roads are mostly in great condition. I can get to a doctor usually within 2-3 days, sometimes even same day. While I like to complain we pay a lot of taxes, its a lot better than the alternative. I would much rather live in a place where taxes benefit everyone, rather than me having 20% more income to spend on expensive health insurance, and seeing suffering everywhere. Only place we lack is military, but being a tiny country that is a given really. We have 27 F35 jets, which is a lot for us when our active personelle is only 25k, its 5.4 F-35 pr million people, where the US has 1.7 F-35 pr million people. So while volume is lower, its a lot for us really.

Increase in manufacturing, yes, but it's low tech, and with very low innovation, on par with Thailand and Poland. And with no software or semiconductor industry to speak of. Unsustainable reproductive rate with low unemployment rate and low immigration, meaning an eventual catastrophic lack of workers and consumers. Not exactly the recipe for a winning horse in the long run..

commentText: The housing collapse was the first crack. Banks gambled, collapsed, and got taxpayer bailouts. Executives handed themselves bonuses with public money while the public paid the price. Occupy Wall Street tried to push back, but nothing truly changed. The same players stayed in power. The rules stayed rigged.  Now we are living through the next phase. Mass layoffs, ghost jobs, AI filters, and stagnant wages are everywhere. Profits soar, shareholders celebrate, and executives cash out while telling workers to be grateful for scraps.  Meritocracy is gone. Optics replaced it. Corporate success is no longer built on value or skill, but on who can perform the best image while cutting the people they parade for PR. Behind the curtain, the human element is gone, and the fa√ßade grows thicker.  AI is not the enemy. The real danger is AI CEOs and executives who treat technology as their personal crown. They are not building; they are competing to out-narcissist each other, blinded by ego and greed. Investors fuel this arms race because it spikes their portfolios, no matter the long-term damage. Behind closed doors, the C-suite and shareholders pat themselves on the back while carving out what remains of the middle class.  This is not about politics. It is about power. The ultra-wealthy control the levers and have no interest in building a system that works for anyone else. This is the second reckoning. The first was the manufacturing carve-out that gutted entire communities. This one is a technological carve-out, and its effects are already eroding the workforce from within.  If you feel invisible, you are not imagining it. This market is not broken; it is built to extract and discard. Until people stop accepting optics for progress and demand substance, the machine will keep grinding through generation after generation.  The ultra-wealthy will not save us. They are too busy competing to see who can burn it down the fastest.

commentText: Why don't many people get a job in Germany? It's simple ‚Äî they don't meet the specific requirements of the companies here. It's not the same as in our home country. While we may be considered highly skilled and reliable workers back home, in Germany, you need to align with the local expectations ‚Äî including soft skills, communication abilities, and especially fluency in German (ideally at the C1 level). German language certificates are not always necessary ‚Äî what really matters is how well you can communicate during the interview. Also, based on my own experience and conversations with HR at my company, there is a common perception that many Indian candidates exaggerate or misrepresent their experience on their CVs, which creates mistrust.  Taking courses at German universities, even short-term Weiterbildung programs, can really help. Don‚Äôt rely solely on your Indian degrees ‚Äî adapting to the local system makes a big difference.  ‚Äî Response from a skilled immigrant working in Germany for 8 years to the indian girl in video (11:10)

commentText:
I'm an engineer from Romania working and living in Germany for more than 8 years now.
 When I came over I did so with a direct contract, though, I did invest time in learning the language at least to a B2 level when I considered looking for a job here. And, while I have 8 years here, my language skills are far from what I want them to be, so I still, periodically, do language courses.
 Since then, with COVID and the drop in German Automotive industry, my company closed but my CEO collected a few of us and started a new one. So, in my 8 years, I collected unemployment for only 1 month.
 Switching out of the Automotive industry (where my main experience was) took about 1.5 - 2 years of constant learning, interviewing and self-correcting.
 I had a lot of interviews where I got to the end stage of the process but it took time, attention to what I could improve after each interview and a significant amount of energy and research. So, work through it, I'm not saying its 100% going to happen, but chances for skilled workers, with German language skills (even poor ones), are quite good in my experience.
 As for German bureaucracy, I come from Romania :) Germany does have more bureaucracy but I find it's functional and quite efficient. The social and taxation systems would probably not work as well without it. However, I do think a lot is over-regulated here and this is consistent with the opinion of my German colleagues :).
 
 What feel is missing and is becoming problematic is digitalization and quality of services. Most, from state provided services (finance, medical, city offices), to private, service oriented, businesses like banks and telecommunication are outdated, overpriced and of mediocre quality.
 
 All in, Germany is, for me, a lot better than Romania, the caveat being: your family and long-time friends are now a long way away. This is not a small factor in your quality of life. There are a lot of things to improve, but this is as much a chance as an issue, since you can be part of improving some aspects and helping your adoptive country.

commentText: I've been to Walmart for 2 years.  It's tough. Even at minimum wage, I had management riding me nonstop to be faster every night I worked.  This was a minimum wage job, yet they treated it like Amazon warehouse where they keep pushing you every day you work to be faster and do more in less time.  I was written up for the dumbest stuff.  One night I was stocking I had 4 mixed pallets on one end of my aisle and 1 pallet of just my stuff at the other.  Management called me to the office and said they're writing me up for not working because that 1 pallet is still sitting there at the end of my aisle.  I explained he obviously didn't see the other 4 mixed pallets which my stuff on top buried everyone else's stuff underneath so I was trying to move that off and stock it because you're not supposed to leave boxes strewn across the floor.  Management said they didn't see it and apologized, but said they still had to write me up because they had already called me to the office and it would look bad on them for pulling me away from my work for nothing.  That was back in 2015.  I'm sure Walmart is a lot harder today.  I changed jobs went to a grocery store doing minimum wage.  The grocery store refused to provide benefits, so everyone was scheduled less than 20hrs/wk.  I had just graduated from college (in my 30s) and had 10 years of customer service/retail exp under my belt and they treat me like I'm below the high school kids they were hiring that sit around drinking gatorade and playing on their phones.  Anyway, minimum wage jobs for the past 10 years couldn't afford an apartment, and I'm sure nowadays they can't either.  My old apartment up near the university was across the street from the grocery store used to be $600/month.  Today, it's practically doubled in rent, and the neighborhood now has a lot of problems with drugs.  A nice apartment in that university town you're looking at paying $3k+ for a single.  I left to China in 2019 because I couldn't find a job with my BA degree from the university right there in that town.  The Career Center at the university kept telling me to apply for GEICO insurance because they just opened new offices and needed help.  Her husband worked there.  I applied and went through round 1 of interviews 3 times.  They always ghost me after that.  So one day I called GEICO and asked to speak with the HR because I really wanted to know yes or no whether I got the job.  They told me the HR will be working on Thursdays.  I called back on Thursday, and the HR was out of town down in Florida on a family vacation.  I'm sitting there like, "you could have told me she was going to be out of the office this thursday, call back next thursday, but you didn't."  Felt like they just were making up stories and the job postings on Indeed might have been fake to appear like they're hiring when they were not.  I was also upset with the career center for not helping me find work.  You would think the school would be helping graduates find work because it'd show that their university degrees actually have value!  Instead, they didn't help me.  I had to go out and find my own job teaching in China.  I wish I could end there, but covid started 6 months after I arrived.  Their visa situation was chaos and my visa expired during a lockdown, so I couldn't get another work visa and I had to return home.  Now I'm jobless, living at home, taking care of my grandmother that was recently diagnosed with Alzheimer's disease.  If she goes into a nursing home, we'll lose the house.  I've tried finding work when I came home from China, but employers just laugh me out the door.  The only type of job hiring right now is heavy industrial, and I don't have any heavy industrial skills.  I'm an academic, not a tradesman.  You say the job market is on the edge?  I'd say it's already collapsed when even young generation are struggling to find entry level positions and salaries everywhere are not keeping up with inflation and the rising cost of living.

commentText: I moved to Bulgaria as a self-employed EU national. It's not at all like moving from California to Idaho; there is quite a process to go through. Incl. depositing 12x mininum local salary, buying private health insurance, etc. I had to apply for a Bulstat number, and to do that you are required to go through local lawyers/accountants. Good ones are hard to find and charge a lot; plus they love to unexpectedly up their fees by 20%-30% because "inflation."  The income tax I pay is 10% minus 4% flat expenses = 6%. Sounds fantastic. Except the mandatory social security contributions are ‚Ç¨600 per month (regardless of whether you‚Äôve had any income during that month or not). In much wealthier Czech/Slovakia, those are about ‚Ç¨200 per month. And if you are a day late with the payments, the government is already charging you interest/penalty.  Lastly, I bought a one-bedroom condo unit. A "management company" swooped in and started charging ‚Ç¨700+ in annual maintenance fees. For that, they provide nothing. No service contract and no one as much as mops the floor  outside my apartment all year long. On top of that, they're now in court with another "management company." Depending on the outcome, I may have to pay the fees a second time, all over again.  1 liter of milk costs ‚Ç¨1 in Austria, ‚Ç¨0.69 in Slovakia. My local Billa sells it for ‚Ç¨2.00 - local Bulgarian milk, mind you. A 100-mile taxi ride to the airport, in my old country, sets you back ‚Ç¨80; here it's ‚Ç¨150. And that's before the upcoming switch to euro in January 2026.  So that's a foreigner's life in Bulgaria. A safe, peaceful place, stunning flora, low taxes, Russian and English widely understood, a stone's throw to Greece... And also a lot of screwy stuff and strong-arm tactics.

commentText: About bringing your spouse with you to EU countries, you mentioned Italy and Austria but I have dealt with both as I have both of those citizenships...  In Italy, yes, you can just bring your spouse.  He / She can get a 5 year spousal visa with no language requirements.  Then the spouse can upgrade to permanent residency.  Austria, on the other hand, requires your spouse to have an A1 German language certificate as a start to get a 1 year visa to stay with you.  If your spouse resists wanting to learn another language, this can make it harder to keep the family together.  (this situation only applies if your spouse is NOT an EU citizen otherwise they have the right of free movement without further language restrictions)  If I am not mistaken, when that visa comes up for renewal after only one year, the spouse has to up the skills to A2 German to show that "integration" is progressing.  Like Italy, at the 5 year mark, the spouse can go for permanent residency.  Separately but related to language...  If you come from the US, Austria will let you convert your driver's license to an Austrian one which will then be valid for driving in all of the EU.  Even if you started from scratch, Austria will let you take the classes in English or German.  However, Italy will only let you drive on your US license for 1 year.  Then you MUST start from scratch and go through Italian driver's education in Italian with no option to do it in English.  Just a couple of things to keep in mind.

commentText: I see this argument often that people migrate because they‚Äôre chasing freedom, or better values, or some philosophical dream of the West. I don‚Äôt buy it‚Äînot for most. Especially for people coming from poorer countries.  In reality, the majority of migration patterns make sense when you follow jobs or government welfare.  Take the U.S., Canada, Germany, or the UK. Why are they popular destinations? Not just because they‚Äôre ‚Äúfree‚Äù countries, but because they offer either (a) better job markets in the Western version of capitalism, or (b) generous social systems. And yes, sometimes both.  Look at Sweden, Germany, or the Netherlands‚Äîcountries with robust welfare states. A lot of migrants aim there because once you‚Äôre in the system, there‚Äôs a safety net: housing, healthcare, education, etc. It‚Äôs not exactly about bootstrapping yourself up through entrepreneurship. Thing is it does not help those whom are native. If anything it puts more drain on their system.  Meanwhile, other migrants aim for places like the U.S. or Canada where it‚Äôs more about economic opportunity and work visas, not free housing.  Then there‚Äôs the language and culture aspect. Migrating from the U.S. to the UK or Ireland? Totally makes sense. There‚Äôs linguistic and cultural overlap. But U.S. to Bulgaria? That‚Äôs way more rare. Just like a Bulgarian moving to China isn‚Äôt exactly common either.  Why? Because if someone was purely chasing economic growth and opportunity, China‚Äîwith its massive industrial expansion and growing middle class‚Äîshould be a hotspot. But it‚Äôs not. Why? Because that person isn‚Äôt necessarily chasing raw growth or capitalism. They‚Äôre chasing a Western-style social system with free education, healthcare, housing benefits, and residency rights.  So it‚Äôs less about ‚Äúfreedom‚Äù and more about which country hands out the better freebie deal.  If the average migrant was an entrepreneur at heart, they‚Äôd go where the frontier is wide open‚Äîmaybe parts of Asia, Africa, or even South America. But most don‚Äôt. They head to where they can plug into an existing system and live decently, even if they don‚Äôt become rich.  Not saying that‚Äôs wrong, just saying let‚Äôs be honest about it and cut the BS.

commentText: For about 20 years now, I've seen a heck of a lot of EU bashing on EU countries and how the economy is performance or how unemployment rates are, especially from the UK and the US.  But when you look at it beyond simply GDP numbers that tells us very little and in a lot of ways are quite misleading, European countries have some of the best quality of life living in the world.  In the end, I don't think it's about how well the economy is doing, but how much of that wealth is reaching the people from the bottom up that matters, after all, what good is wealth generating if it ends up in too few hands like we see in the US a lot?  We seriously do need better ways of measuring wealth of people that also put a focus on quality of life and from the bottom up, after all, lifting up the poor to middle classes, you more or less lift up everyone.

commentText: The first main problem is that businesses are being dissuaded from investing in creating jobs due to the employers' NI rise (effectively a tax on your job), the Employment Rights Bill adding further costs, and the lack of a clear economic strategy from the Treasury.   The second problem is that at the low end of the income scale, you're often far better off choosing benefits as a career than a minimum wage job due to the differences in support schemes and taxes. Hence the massive increase in claims for nebulous conditions like "anxiety" or "ADHD", especially among young people.   The solution is to look to Denmark, where employment rights are surprisingly limited and make it easy to hire and fire employees. However, they can do this because fired workers get quite a generous amount of support from the welfare system, but that support is limited in time and scope. You're strongly pushed into training courses or looking for a job, and it'll get yanked after a couple of years. That means there's a good safety net that is only temporary, and businesses are more willing to hire people, safe in the knowledge that they can be binned off if they don't work out.

videoTitle: The Brutal Reality of the Tech Job Market
videoDescription: The tech job market right now is brutal. Layoffs, endless applications, and constant rejections. It feels impossible to land an offer.
commentText: I've come to the conclusion that I no longer want to chase after a language or framework. This changes all the time. I've also decided that I will no longer subject myself to being treated like a commodity at a cattle auction. In the end, all of this is designed to make you accept doing more for less. I think at some point we give in and accept unrealistic things because the "market demands it," or the influencer you follow or the group of followers in the bubble you're in dictates that this is the culture, technology, or method to be adopted. Yes, I went through a financial setback and had to accept working in other segments. But that didn't kill my desire to work with software. Today, I think the path is to work as an entrepreneur and consultant for small businesses, creating solutions for the region you live in or where you can work without creating a burden on your life. Another mistake I see is the industrialization of the IT workforce. We didn't start that way; we started in a garage or on a small project; we're not cattle.

commentText: There is no such thing as a dream job unless you are self employed in your home town with good income, surrounded by your grannies and nannies and eating home food every day sitting on the lap of your mother! Every job is a challenge and a compromise and the further you get out from your comfort home or country the more challenging it gets. That is where Indian youths who have been pampered at home fail abroad with social adjustment in a new society. They are home sick all the time. They should be concentrating on learning new language, new culture, new skills, seeing new places, experiencing the diversity and nature and even enjoying the quietness and lonliness filled with personal advancement. Glad that you pointed out many of these things here. Europe or any where else is definitely not a bed of roses. Nobody is waiting for you with open arms to give you a job, a home or a car. It is a healthy struggle here all the way minus nepotism, corruption, unequality and injustice which you are hopefully trying to get away from.

videoTitle: Why it‚Äôs so difficult to get a job right now (it's not A.I.)
videoDescription: Check out our advertising sponsor Cape and use code MANDM33 to get 33% off your first six months ...
commentText: For inexperienced workers, I think another huge factor is the increasingly short-term way companies are run. It simply doesn't make sense to hire and train junior people when your company outlook is measured in quarters rather than decades, because they represent high risk of failure on critical short-term deadlines, compounded by high indirect cost to the productivity of the senior people that train them and could otherwise be focussed fully on critical tasks, both of which are naturally compounded by AI as an alternative, but existed well before it.  Add the pattern of company hopping that's more and more popular, which effectively means that training new people is paying for their next employer's benefit more than your own, and it's not hard to see why companies just don't want to deal with entry level people any more.  Of course, that's unsustainable in the long run, but for that, see both of the above: in a business where your incentives are quarterly and *you* expect to jump after a few years too, the long run is some future employee's problem, not yours.  Eventually I think we'll end up needing policy incentives for what I think of as "sustainable hiring" where there are subsidies or similar cost offsetting measures in place to encourage the creation of early career positions and training, because as senior people leave the workforce into retirement, there won't be enough young people gaining the experience to replace them, and that's not something companies are likely to fix for themselves in the current environment.

commentText: A big issue with the Unemployment Rate is that it is an artificially depressed number, as there are several criteria that get you removed from that rate, particularly those who have given up and are no longer looking despite not having a job. It also excludes those who are chronically Underemployed (<20h/week). the LISEP "True Rate of Unemployment" study insists that the actual rate of functional unemployment is closer to 25% than it is to the official figure of 4%.  Not that we'd know what the current rate of Unemployment is right now since we haven't gotten Jobs or GDP reports since October.

commentText: The unemployment in Germany has risen to roughly 2,8 mio. people, yet that is still historically a quite low level. 1,6 mio. of these people have no degree / apprenticeship at all and 50% of unemployed have no German citizenship and might struggle with language, culture and education. Of the remaining 1,2 mio. people with degrees a third is 55+ with difficulties in acquiring new skills and a substantial number (I guess around 200k additionally) lives in so called lost regions of former industries both in the east and west. If you look at these numbers for Germany, the problem seems to be hiring freezes as the only ones that still hire are the state / government or any adjacent jobs to them. It doesn't look as bleak mid-term (roughly 400k more people retire from the workforce than young people entering it per year), yet that doesn't help in the short-term.   It is such a paradox situation, there is a lack of skilled workers and no one wants to hire the ones that are there due to the economic uncertainty and economic cooldown. Companies try to 'sit-it-out' till it gets better, a lot of my friends are overworked as companies put on more pressure instead of hiring new people. AI doesn't affect their jobs directly.   Guess everyone needs to skill up the next months to either prepare for a post-AI world (there will be jobs, yet the skills required are different) or go for another direction altogether (quite some people take double degrees now). The crazy thing is that multiple things happen all at once making it more difficult to find the right personal response to it.

commentText: >Unemployment is close to the historical average Using unemployment isn't entirely accurate, as you have to be actively looking for work to be unemployed; US 2014-2016 data are technically around average as Obama's "unemployment below 8%" claims, but a large part of that is a lot of unemployed workers stopped looking for work, and 2020-2023 caused a lot of people to retire early or just die because of COVID, so they don't technically count as unemployed and dead people don't count in labor force participation either. Underemployment due to people taking gig jobs or lower paying jobs can also misrepresent employment. Also, H-1B immigration necessarily requires having a job, so mass importing employed people from other countries during the Biden years will dilute the apparent unemployment rate among natives. It's a very imperfect metric.

commentText: It's not AI, it's low hiring/low firing economy, especially in the US. Companies are hoarding workers and not firing anyone, which keeps the unemployment rate low, but they're also not hiring any new people, which makes it hard to find a job. It's symptom of the weird permanently pre-recession economy the US is in where the economy is always on the brink of a recession but never goes under all the while headline numbers stay strong. Which is mostly a consequence of K shaped economy where headline numbers like GDP growth and consumption are propped up by the top 10% richest Americans who keep spending while everyone else cuts back.

commentText: 1:51 and 2:43‚Äî the official unemployment rate is almost constant in the US/UK/Germany, except COVID period. There's like 1.5x or less variation, that cannot be called "must harder to find a job". And the rest of the video is trying to explain why unemployment rate is rising (insignificantly), while in the beginning we saw that it's not rising (almost).  My one hypothesis for now is that while unemployment rate is constant, it may be still harder to change a job ‚Äî it may be less people taking more time to find a new job, so the total number time√ópeople is approximately constant. In case of IT it could be, for example, that companies consider much more candidates before choosing one due to some cultural shift after COVID, and that causes candidates to send much more resumes and spend much more time to find a new job (I mean AI resume filtering stage + more interviews for more candidates before hiring + more remote jobs to choose from a larger candidate pool). That's an assumption, I don't have hard data for this except for long term unemployment that grows faster than simple unemployment since early 2023. My second hypothesis is that the official unemployment statistics may not reflect the real unemployment for some reason.

videoTitle: how we‚Äôre *actually* getting jobs in 2025 #jobsearch
commentText: You may get bites from very small firms. For larger firms, this is worse than contacting recruiter directly. Interviewing screening and such are usually side things for hiring managers and are more focused on their primary senior job duties. They will more than likely get annoyed and ignore it completely. Especially these days where applicant to role ratios are wack. Chances are they already have dozens of folks contacting them directly.  Networking helps a lot: job fairs, friends, family, hobby groups. Have multiple people look over your resume. Practice interviewing. Other than that it's a number game.

commentText: As a Recruiter who was working with Big Tech until April this year, I can tell you that a lot of times companies close the jobs from their end on the Applicant tracking systems. But jobs continue to show because 1] there is a sync error/lag between the system and the various job portals integrated with it. So jobs remain published on portals even though the company is no longer accepting applications. 2] Several job portals/aggregators keep reposting old/expired job ads to attract candidates and expand their databases. They lure candidates with free to create accounts. Then, they sell this database to company recruiters. Bigger the database, higher the price. They don't care whether jobs shown are legit. As an aggregator, their liability is limited.

commentText: When of the biggest challenges is staying current with your skills. Software and platforms are undergoing generational changes every year. If you are out of the market for 6 months, there may  no longer be a need for your skill set. You couldn't even qualify for the job you left as they are using newer or at least upgraded platforms.  This is extremely stressful and frustrating to someone who is just trying to get a toe hold in the market and stay there. One thing not talked about much is that so much of this work is now done through contractors and vendors. You get a 6 month contract, you're nearing the end of it so you start looking for your next gig. Recuiters don't need you in 3 weeks at the end of your contract. They need you today. That job posting wont even be there when your contract ends. This virtually guarantees periods of unemployment.

commentText: Current Challenges in the Tech Job Market Massive Layoffs: Over 260,000 tech jobs were cut globally in 2023, followed by 150,000+ in 2024 and 25,000+ in 2025.  Automation Impact: Nearly 50% of executives report increased automation, replacing mid-level engineering and administrative roles.  Fake Job Listings: 55% of tech companies post fake job ads, with 70% of recruiters considering it acceptable.  Low Interview Rates: Only 8% of tech job applicants receive interview responses, down from 12% in previous years.  Corporate Ghosting: Many applicants receive no response even after multiple interview rounds.  Longer Job Searches: The average time to secure a tech job in the U.S. has risen from 3 to 5+ months.  Mental Health Strain: Endless rejections and ghosting have led to widespread frustration among job seekers.  Decline in Entry-Level Roles: Entry-level tech job postings dropped by 30% in the UK and over 70% for software developers in the U.S. (2023-2025).  Rising Unemployment: IT sector unemployment reached 5.5% in May 2025, surpassing the national average.  Shifts in Hiring and Job Demand AI-Driven Job Growth: AI-related roles (machine learning, data science, cloud computing) are growing despite declines in traditional tech jobs.  Changing Skill Requirements: Companies now prioritize practical certifications over traditional degrees.  Fewer General IT Jobs: Tech support and generic software engineering roles are shrinking.  New Job Creation: AI is generating demand for specialized roles (AI scientists, cybersecurity experts, data architects).  Struggles for New Graduates: Unemployment for recent graduates is at 7%, the highest in a decade, with 30-40% fewer entry-level openings.  Visa Challenges: Over 10,000 H1B visa holders lost jobs in 2023, with many struggling to find new placements.  Future Projections & Recovery Selective Recovery: The job market is rebounding slowly but unevenly, favoring niche AI and automation-related roles.  18% Growth in Tech Jobs: The U.S. Department of Labor predicts 350,000+ new tech jobs annually by 2034, mostly in AI and cybersecurity.  No Return to Pre-2022 Levels: The market won‚Äôt regain its 2021-2022 hiring peaks; instead, it will become more specialized.  Permanent Structural Changes: Mass hiring and extravagant perks are fading as companies prioritize efficiency and automation.  Adaptation Required: Job seekers must upskill in AI, cloud computing, and cybersecurity to remain competitive.

commentText: Thanks for this video, I am retired from IT, I was in IT project management for more than 20 years. More than 20 years ago, I started as a school teacher in Singapore (high school math and cs) but left teaching to join tech industry. AT that time, the multimedia side of tech was hot and hip. I left a full government job for multimedia! üòÖ over the years, I‚Äôve managed both systems and multimedia development projects. Now, I return to the classroom in Canada, teaching math, cs and tech related subjects in high school. I am looking closely at the scores of unemployed new cs graduates because part of my job is to encourage students to make IT their life long careerüòÖ. I think the current situation is an over supply of IT professionals many of whom did not major in AI development and machine learning (robotics) or automation. AI has changed the nature of tech jobs. New graduates must adapt to new realities, adapt to using AI instead, in the work place, do not define what is coding and what is not coding, instead just get the job done in the most efficient time saving way. I also think that most tech jobs are taken by new immigrants (in Canada), only top local graduates from top universities find work or like what you mentioned, those with connections. Over the years, I‚Äôve come to think that cs graduates should be licensed like engineers, accountants, doctors, nurses and teachers. As for current job situation, they should apply into management roles if there are fewer entry level positions. AI has created new positions, even a team of robots need to be managed and maintained. I don‚Äôt see IT (including multimedia) management positions going away anytime soon. In fact, coding jobs are not going away either, it‚Äôs coding AI software that is in demand, the bar has been raised very high, there is a merger of mechanical, electrical engineering with computer science.

commentText: The likelihood of coming to Germany as a student and securing a job afterward is quite limited because Germany generally encourages students to immigrate temporarily and then return to their home countries after graduation. Unlike the US, UK, and other countries where students often stay and work permanently, this is not typically the case in Germany. While it's possible to find lower-level jobs that don't match your qualifications simply because you're fluent in German, this isn't a sustainable long-term strategy. High taxes and living costs mean that you probably won't become wealthy; instead, you'll live an average life. Additionally, there's intense competition, and employers tend to favor native Germans over migrants.   German employers also usually prefer candidates from prestigious US and British universities like Yale or Cambridge over student immigrants with a university degree from Germany. This is a fact. They often welcome international students primarily for economic reasons, not necessarily to provide more employment opportunities. I know an American who studied here,  became fluent in German (C1 level), speaking almost like a native, but she told me most employers rejected her in favor of native Germans. She eventually returned to the US.   So, believing that studying in Germany will guarantee a job afterward is an illusion. There are already highly qualified refugees from other countries who are unemployed here. Many YouTube channels don't have a thorough understanding of the German system; while some are relatively trustworthy, they still lack complete knowledge and experience. Comparatively, this YouTube is genuine, although the guy didn't cover some other facts, which I can understand may be due to a lack of knowledge of the German system.

commentText: The problem is YouTube is full of videos promising people financial freedom by simply learning how to talk to AI.    It doesn't help when top tech leaders are also saying the days of software development by human is over.   These tech leaders also do not understand the details because they don't do the work themselves either.   They only get to talk big in big events.  I am an experienced AI developer.   I tried my best several times to vibe code a complete product.   I failed in every single one of the experiment.   In all cases,  I get to 80% but that 20% will take forever and lots of frustration.   After that going into the code to fix it myself took longer than I would by developing them myself.   The only way that work for me is to use AI as my assistant.  I will have to do all the thinking and architecting.  I will translate the thinking into very specific instructions for AI to follow.   Only by doing that,  I could complete a project with productivity gain.

commentText: That's ridiculous! Not that long ago, companies would train their own staff from "the bottom", which allowed more people to enter the company through entry-level jobs and progress to more skilled and senior roles as they worked and learned over the years. Now they require qualifications that are never tailored to the specific job or company, and quite often these are a requirement for entry-level jobs. Back when I was in Spain during the construction boom, there was no shortage of "qualified builders", lots of 16-year-old kids would leave school and start learning from 0 as they worked in construction, and nobody had a problem with that. But here we need "qualified construction workers", or we don't give them a chance. Greed and stupidity ruined the job market.

commentText: 1) cost of living changes do not equal wage growth, not even close, over the last 50 years.  Rent, groceries, healthcare, car costs have grown much faster than wages on median. 2) outsourcing is a much higher threat than AI.  Millions of foreign workers that speak English are taking western (UK, USA, Canada) jobs at a much faster rate than AI in the next 5-10 years. 3) remote work makes #2 worse.  I get it, I love remote working, but if you think your company cares enough about you to not replace you you‚Äôre dead wrong.  If you think you‚Äôre irreplaceable you might be right, but that won‚Äôt stop your company from replacing you with 2-3 workers in a lower wage country and saving half or 2/3 your costs even if it losses them money in the end. 4) Productivity isn‚Äôt falling, companies are in a non spoken agreement to pay as absolutely little as they possibly can and making the hiring process as painful as possible to make people unwilling to change.  The growth in productivity is going to the top 0.1%. 5) I am a mid level professional with nearly 20 years experience in my field, I applied to over 2,000 to get 4 offers, I was well qualified for all of them, this is the worst job market I‚Äôve seen except for 2008-2011.  Good luck if you‚Äôre recently let go.
